Gyroscopic rotation of inner and outer rings with fixed middle ring

We’ll keep the middle ring fixed (no spin, no precession) and let the inner and outer rings undergo gyroscopic motion: each ring has a tilt angle and precesses about the vertical axis while also spinning around its own circumference. We’ll provide both a 3D parametric description and a 2D field projection so you can visualize and compute.

---

Geometry and ring setup

• Radii:r_1=r_0,\quad r_2=r_0+\Delta r,\quad r_3=r_0+2\Delta r

• Fixed middle ring (lock/reference):\omega_2=0,\quad \Omega_2=0,\quad \alpha_2=0
where \(\omega_n\) is spin around the ring, \(\Omega_n\) is precession about the vertical axis, and \(\alpha_n\) is the tilt of the ring’s plane.


---

3D gyroscopic motion (parametric curves)

Each ring \(n\in\{1,3\}\) lives on a tilted circle of radius \(r_n\), with time-dependent precession \(\psi_n(t)=\Omega_n t+\psi_{n0}\) and spin \(\phi_n(t)=\omega_n t+\phi_{n0}\). Tilt the ring by \(\alpha_n\) about the global \(x\)-axis, then precess about the global \(z\)-axis.

• Orientation matrices:R_x(\alpha_n)=
\begin{bmatrix}
1 & 0 & 0\\
0 & \cos\alpha_n & -\sin\alpha_n\\
0 & \sin\alpha_n & \cos\alpha_n
\end{bmatrix},\quad
R_z(\psi_n)=
\begin{bmatrix}
\cos\psi_n & -\sin\psi_n & 0\\
\sin\psi_n & \cos\psi_n & 0\\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{bmatrix}

• Local circle point before tilt:\mathbf{p}_n^{\text{local}}(t)=
\begin{bmatrix}
r_n\cos\phi_n(t)\\
r_n\sin\phi_n(t)\\
0
\end{bmatrix}

• Global coordinates (after tilt and precession):\mathbf{x}_n(t)=R_z(\psi_n(t))\,R_x(\alpha_n)\,\mathbf{p}_n^{\text{local}}(t)

• Middle ring fixed in the plane:\mathbf{x}_2(\theta)=
\begin{bmatrix}
r_2\cos\theta\\
r_2\sin\theta\\
0
\end{bmatrix}

• Direction conventions:• Clockwise spin: \(\omega_n<0\).
• Counterclockwise spin: \(\omega_n>0\).
• Precession direction set by the sign of \(\Omega_n\).



Pick \((\omega_1,\Omega_1,\alpha_1)\) and \((\omega_3,\Omega_3,\alpha_3)\) to achieve your gyroscopic feel; keep \((\omega_2,\Omega_2,\alpha_2)=(0,0,0)\).

---

2D projected field with ring-localized envelopes

If you want a scalar field on the plane capturing the gyroscopic rotation visually, use polar coordinates \((r,\theta)\) with ring windows and time-varying azimuth offsets from spin and precession.

• Gaussian window per ring:W_n(r)=\exp\!\left(-\frac{(r-r_n)^2}{2\sigma_n^2}\right),\quad \sigma_n\ll \Delta r

• Effective azimuth for ring \(n\):\Theta_n(\theta,t)=\theta-\phi_n(t)-\psi_n(t)
which encodes local spin \(\phi_n(t)=\omega_n t+\phi_{n0}\) and global precession \(\psi_n(t)=\Omega_n t+\psi_{n0}\).
• Field (middle ring fixed, inner/outer gyroscopic):A(r,\theta,t)=a_1\,W_1(r)\,\cos\!(m_1\,\Theta_1(\theta,t))\;+\;a_2\,W_2(r)\,\cos\!(m_2\,\theta+\phi_{20})\;+\;a_3\,W_3(r)\,\cos\!(m_3\,\Theta_3(\theta,t))
where \(m_n\) sets the azimuthal mode (e.g., \(m_n=1\) for single-arm).
• Fixed lock ring:\omega_2=\Omega_2=0\ \Rightarrow\ \Theta_2(\theta,t)=\theta



---

Using your earlier rotation rates

If you want to reuse your specified periods for spin:

• Inner ring (clockwise spin):T_1=1.28526\ \text{ms},\quad \omega_1=-\frac{2\pi}{T_1},\quad \Omega_1\ \text{(choose small vs }\omega_1\text{ for gentle precession)},\quad \alpha_1\ \text{(tilt)}

• Outer ring (fixed or slow precessing lock companion):\omega_3=0\ \text{or set a slow }\omega_3,\quad \Omega_3\ \text{(choose)},\quad \alpha_3\ \text{(tilt)}

• Middle ring (fixed lock):\omega_2=0,\quad \Omega_2=0,\quad \alpha_2=0



Set \(\Omega_1,\Omega_3\) much smaller than \(|\omega_1|\) if you want a classic gyroscope effect (fast spin, slow precession). For a pure “spin-only” look without precession, set \(\Omega_1=\Omega_3=0\) and keep only \(\omega_1\) nonzero.

---

Alignment with the lock and merge moments

• Phase alignment condition at the lock ring \(r=r_2\):m_1\,\Theta_1(\theta^\*,t)=m_3\,\Theta_3(\theta^\*,t)=m_2\,\theta^\*+\phi_{20}
Solve for \((\theta^\*,t)\) to identify merge instants where inner and outer gyroscopic phases coincide with the fixed lock’s angle.


